         b'on &raquo;</a></div>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class="post-145 post t'
         b'ype-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-conference c'
         b'ategory-paper category-prediction category-recommender-systems categ'
         b'ory-research" id="post-145">\n\t\t\t<h2>Filtering By Trust</h2>\n'
         b'\n\t\t\t<div class="entry">\n\t\t\t\t<p>A lot of the posts on thi'
         b's blog discuss the idea of computers using trust in different scenar'
         b'ios. Since starting as a research student, and reading a lot of <a h'
         b'ref="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/2007/10/31/lightweight-distributed-'
         b'trust-propagation/">good papers</a> about trust, I still find the id'
         b'ea slightly strange: is trust something that can actually be quantif'
         b'ied? Are these computers actually reasoning about <em>trust</em>? (w'
         b'hat is trust?)</p>\n<p>Trust, however, seems to have a place in o'
         b'ur research. It gives us a metaphor to describe how interactions bet'
         b'ween &#8220;strangers&#8221; should happen, a platform to build appl'
         b'ications that feed off these ideas, and a language to describe and a'
         b'nalyse the emergent properties that we observe in these systems. So,'
         b' even if a trust relationship may be a concept that cannot be boiled'
         b' down to a deterministic protocol, it gives researchers a model of t'
         b'he world they are exploring.</p>\n<p>I decided to apply this meta'
         b'phor to collaborative filtering, an algorithm that aims to generate '
         b'recommendations by assigning neighbours to each user. Usually this a'
         b'ssignment is done by computed similarity, which has its downfalls: h'
         b'ow similar are two people who have never rated items in common? What'
         b' is the <a href="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/2007/09/21/collaborativ'
         b'e-filtering-is-strange/">best way of measuring similarity</a>? Apply'
         b'ing the metaphor of trust, instead, aims at capturing the value that'
         b' each neighbour gives to a user&#8217;s recommendations over time, a'
         b'nd value is not only derived from agreement- but also from the abili'
         b'ty a neighbour has to provide information. While similarity-based al'
         b'gorithms use neighbour ratings, interactions based on trust acknowle'
         b'dge that information received from others is subject to interpretati'
         b'on, as there may be a strong <em>semantic distance</em> between the '
         b'way two users apply ratings to items.</p>\n<p>Trust is a richer c'
         b'oncept than similarity by favouring neighbours who can give you info'
         b'rmation about the items you seek and offering a means of learning to'
         b' interpret the information received from them. Evaluating this techn'
         b'ique improves on the basic similarity-driven algorithms, both in ter'
         b'ms of accuracy and coverage: modeling the problem as an instance of '
         b'a trust-management scenario seems to offer an escape from traditiona'
         b'l pitfalls of similarity-based approaches. I leave all the details t'
         b'o the paper, &#8220;Trust-based Collaborative Filtering,&#8221; whic'
         b'h is due to appear in<a href="http://www.ntnu.no/videre/konferanse/I'
         b'FIPTM08/"> IFIPTM 2008</a> (thanks to Daniele for his great comments'
         b' and feedback).</p>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t<p class="postmeta'
